body:
The easiest way to present this problem is to use an example of an implementation of the Either type.

```php
<?php

/**
 * @template L
 * @template R
 */
interface Either
{

}

/**
 * @template L
 * @template R
 * @template-implements Either<L,R>
 */
final class Right implements Either
{
    /**
     * @param R $value
     */
    public function __construct($value) {}
}


/**
 * @template L
 * @template R
 * @template-implements Either<L,R>
 */
final class Left implements Either
{
    /**
     * @param L $value
     */
    public function __construct($value) { }
}

class A {}
class B {}

/**
 * @return Either<A,B>
 */
function result(bool $a = true): Either
{
    if($a) {
        return new Left(new A());
    }

    return new Right(new B());
}
```

As you can see, the result of the analysis (https://psalm.dev/r/c9994142bc) shows errors:

```
ERROR: MixedReturnTypeCoercion - github.php:43:12 - The declared return type 'Either<A, B>' for result is more specific than the inferred return type 'Left<A, mixed>|Right<mixed, B>'
 * @return Either<A,B>


ERROR: MixedReturnTypeCoercion - github.php:48:16 - The type 'Left<A, mixed>' is more general than the declared return type 'Either<A, B>' for result
        return new Left(new A());


ERROR: MixedReturnTypeCoercion - github.php:51:12 - The type 'Right<mixed, B>' is more general than the declared return type 'Either<A, B>' for result
    return new Right(new B());
```

I wonder if there is a better solution than using an annotation:
```
@psalm-suppress MixedReturnTypeCoercion
```
